# Force CRLF line endings on .cmd/.bat scripts — Windows cmd.exe refuses to
# parse .cmd files with LF-only line endings (it concatenates `@echo off` and
# `setlocal` into a single unrecognizable command and silently aborts before
# any user-defined command runs). Keeping these in CRLF at checkout time
# means the installed bridge script is correct even if a developer edits it
# on a Unix machine or commits it via a tool that doesn't preserve endings.
*.cmd text eol=crlf
*.bat text eol=crlf

# Everything else keeps LF — the renderer bundle, tsconfig, etc. don't need
# CRLF, and most editors handle LF cleanly.
*.ts text eol=lf
*.js text eol=lf
*.json text eol=lf
*.md text eol=lf
*.html text eol=lf
*.css text eol=lf